APPENDIX C GLOSSARY OF TECHNICAL TERMS
GLOSSARY OF TECHNICAL TERMS
AC
Alternating Current.
Electric current that reverses its direction periodically.
Energy from the electrical grid is in the form of AC.
The standard unit for measuring the strength of the electric current.
An electrical device that converts alternating current to direct current for a battery, and may also provide energy for operating other vehicle electrical systems.
It may be located either on-board the vehicle or off-board the vehicle.
The vehicle inlet into which the connector is inserted for charging a vehicle.
A plug or paddle that fits into a charge port located on the vehicle that establishes a connection for the purposes of charging an electric vehicle.
Amps
Charger
Charge port
Connector
Control pilot
The primary control conductor on conductive systems that is connected to equipment ground through control circuitry on the vehicle.
A mating vehicle charge port and compatible connector set.
Coupler
Current
Rate of flow of electrical charge in a medium (or conductor) between two points.
Direct Current.
Electric current flowing in one direction.
Electric Vehicle Supply Equipment includes the conductors, connectors, attachment plugs, and all other fittings, devices, power outlets, or apparatuses, installed specifically for the purposes of delivering energy from the premises wiring to the electric vehicle.
A charging method that allows an electric vehicle to be connected to the most common grounded receptacle (120 VAC, 1-phase).
DC EVSE
Level I
C-1
Level 2
A charging method that utilizes dedicated electric vehicle supply equipment in either private or public locations.
The maximum power levels are 208 to 240 VAC, 1 phase.
A charging method that utilizes dedicated electric vehicle supply equipment to provide direct current energy from an appropriate off-board charger to the electric vehicle.
The maximum power supplied for Level 3 charging equipment should be capable to replenish more than half of the capacity of an EV battery in less than half an hour.
Transformation of alternating current to direct current.
Battery chargers require that electricity be delivered as DC.
A device containing no moving parts and consisting of two or more coils of insulated wire that transfers alternating current by electromagnetic induction from one winding to another at the same frequency but usually with changed voltage and current values.
Difference in electrical potential, expressed in volts.
A practical unit of electromotive force, that specifies the difference in electrical potential between two points.
